#Question a)
# Hierarchical clustering to data using using Euclidean distance

# Dissimilarity matrix
d <- dist(df, method = "euclidean")

# Hierarchical clustering using Complete Linkage
cluster1 <- hclust(d, method = "complete" )

# Plot the obtained dendrogram
plot(cluster1, cex = 0.6, hang = -1)

# # Compute with agnes and with different linkage methods

m <- c( "average", "single", "complete", "ward")
names(m) <- c( "average", "single", "complete", "ward")

# function to compute coefficient
ac <- function(x) {
  agnes(df, method = x)$ac
}

map_dbl(m, ac)
##   average    single  complete      ward 
## 0.7766075 0.6067859 0.8353712 0.9046042

Using Wards method we are getting the highest agglomerative coefficient. Ward method is the best linkage method with agglomerative coefficient 0.9046042.

#Question b)
#Visualizing the dendogram using ward's method

cluster2 <- agnes(df, method = "ward")
pltree(cluster2, cex = 0.6, hang = -1, main = "Dendrogram of agnes")
rect.hclust(cluster2, k = 4, border = 2:5)

# Plotting the Dendogram for divisive hierarchical clustering.
dendo<-diana(df)
dendo$dc
## [1] 0.8302148
pltree(dendo,cex=0.6,hang=-1,"Dendrogram of diana")

# Mapping the clusters to the data points. 
clust <- cutree(cluster2,k=4) 
data<-cbind(data,clust)

# Checking the stability of the cluster
cluster3<-customer
cluster4<-na.omit(cluster3) 

#Data Partition A
train_data<-cluster4[1:60,] 

#Data Partition B
test_data<-cluster4[61:74,] 

TRData<-as.data.frame(scale(train_data[,-c(1:3)]))
TSData<-as.data.frame(scale(test_data[,-c(1:3)]))

#Partition A by using ward method
m1 <- c( "average", "single", "complete", "ward")
names(m) <- c( "average", "single", "complete", "ward")

# function to compute coefficient
ac <- function(x) {
  agnes(TRData, method = x)$ac
}

map_dbl(m1, ac)
## [1] 0.7567786 0.6672134 0.8207517 0.8898441
#Dendogram of Partition A (By using the best method)
cluster5 <- agnes(TRData, method = "ward")
pltree(cluster5, cex = 0.6, hang = -1, main = "Dendrogram of agnes")

cluster6<-cutree(cluster5,k=4)

#Centers of the cluster
result<-as.data.frame(cbind(TRData,cluster6))
mean1<-data.frame(column=seq(1,13,1),mean=rep(0,13))
mean2<-data.frame(column=seq(1,13,1),mean=rep(0,13))
mean3<-data.frame(column=seq(1,13,1),mean=rep(0,13))
mean4<-data.frame(column=seq(1,13,1),mean=rep(0,13))
for(i in 1:13)
{
  mean1[i,2]<-mean(result[result$clust==1,i])
  mean2[i,2]<-mean(result[result$clust==2,i])
  mean3[i,2]<-mean(result[result$clust==3,i])
  mean4[i,2]<-mean(result[result$clust==4,i])
  
}
centroid<-t(cbind(mean1$mean,mean2$mean,mean3$mean,mean4$mean))
colnames(centroid)<-colnames(customer[,-c(1:3)])
